                      /
                      <span>25</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2000-12-08</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>I write to refute the reviewer who gave Jordan's great book one star.  White Over Black is probably the best single work of scholarship in any field on race in American history--still current and trenchant after more than thirty years.  Jordan's Jefferson chapters remain definitive, his examination of Europeans' "first impressions" of Africans is classic, and his basic perspective--that one cannot say that slavery caused racism or vice versa, but intertwined--completely persuasive.  His insistence that racial attitudes intertwine with sexual stereotypes, prejudices, and self-doubts reshaped the field.  The book is brilliantly written and rests on an unmatched mastery of literally thousands of sources.  Anyone interested in the history of race in America should read it.</span>
                  
